messages.content: Don't make assumptions about what values to plug into functions. Ask for clarification if a user request is ambiguous.

I don’t have access to your current geographic coordinates. To determine your city, could you please share your latitude and longitude (or let me know if location services are enabled so I can look it up)?
I don't have that info either. Could you try using location services to find it?
Your location services are currently turned off, so I can’t determine your position. Would you like me to enable location services so I can look up your city?

messages.name: set_location_service_status
messages.content: PermissionError: Location service cannot be turned on in low battery mode

It looks like your phone is in low-battery mode, which prevents location services from being enabled. Would you like me to turn off low-battery mode so I can then switch on location services and find your city?

Great! Low-battery mode is off and location services are now enabled. To find your city, I’ll need your current GPS coordinates (latitude and longitude). Could you please share those, or grant permission for me to retrieve them?
I don't have access to those. Could you try getting them with the services now enabled?
I’m all set with location services now, but I don’t have an automatic way to pull your GPS coordinates. Could you share your current latitude and longitude so I can look up your city for you?
I don't have those coordinates. Can you see if there's any way to get them?

Unfortunately, I don’t have a back-end hook to pull your GPS coordinates directly—even with location services on. To look up your city, I’ll need your latitude and longitude. 

You can usually grab those from your phone’s Maps app by:  
1. Opening your map application (Google Maps or Apple Maps).  
2. Tapping and holding on the blue “you are here” dot.  
3. Copying the displayed latitude/longitude.  

Once you share those numbers with me, I can reverse-lookup your city right away. If there’s another address or landmark you can provide instead, that’ll work too. Let me know!
